	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 08-26-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">07:46 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">Or – How I learned to ‘Just Say No’ to Halfling Warriors<br />
<br />
Shazzog and I had spent our night sleeping on the grassy banks near SoulBinder Jerra. When we awoke, the sun was high and the Plane of Knowledge was as bustling as ever. Vendors were hawking their wares, people were looking for mind candy…and I was looking for my morning coffee.<br />
<br />
So intent was I on hunting down the elusive Double Latte, that I missed the original cry for help. Shazzog did not.<br />
<br />
“Hey, Du…dat gnome in da robe is lookin fer help. He got himself beat down in da Burnin’ Woods…tink we should go help him?”<br />
<br />
“No, Shazz, I’m sure some Cleric with a Water Sprinkler will be along to go help him. My skills aren’t quite up there yet.”<br />
<br />
A few minutes later, latte in hand, Shazzog and I were strolling towards the portal to Paineel when we noticed the fellow with a Burning problem was still looking for help.<br />
<br />
“Look, Du, he part of da Emerald Dragons. Dey part of da Alliance. We gotta help him.”<br />
<br />
“You’re right, Shazz. I’ll go get him, you get your traveling spells ready.”<br />
<br />
And so I did, and so he did. So it was that a short time later, we found ourselves in the Burning Woods. Luckily, it wasn’t in Ice Clad this week…<br />
<br />
Being the grateful sort, the gnome offered to weigh down my purse a bit for my troubles. Needless to say, I could not accept, as he was an Alliance member. I could, and did, ask him to remember me this coming weekend when the Alliance was going to return to Chardok. Seems the OverKing has a note of some importance that I need to retrieve…and I doubt he will hand it over willingly.<br />
<br />
Our task completed and the gnome resting comfortably, we made our way back to the Plane of Knowledge, there to set off for Dulak at last.<br />
<br />
I had no sooner arrived than I received an obscure message from some warrior I had never seen before. All it said was - ***”Hello”***<br />
<br />
Hmmm, perhaps he confused me for someone else? Perhaps he is just a friendly type, and has determined himself to be the Official Greeter of the Plane of Knowledge?<br />
I sent back a friendly ‘Hello’ and continued on my way. His psychic message found me once easily enough, it can find me again if this fellow needs to talk.<br />
<br />
Indeed, no sooner did we reappear on the Toxula Forrest side of the Paineel portal then another message appeared in my mind.<br />
<br />
***“I’m a 49th level warrior with good gear. I’m looking for a Cleric to go to Dulak with me. I can solo things myself, but a CHeal makes things a lot easier.”***<br />
Hmmmm. Normally I avoid picking up strays when Shazzog and I are off adventuring. It so rarely turns out well. Still, the day started off well enough, and the sturdy warriors that normally accompany me were either off harassing the Giants in Kael, or still abed somewhere. <br />
<br />
“What do you think, Shazz? Should we take mercy on this poor warrior, and help him stay alive in Dulak?”<br />
<br />
“Sure, why not. He can’t be gett’n inta too much trouble all by hisself, and we can take care of anyting he can’t handle. Let’s let him join us. We show him how da Klan ov da Grok clean up da docks!”<br />
<br />
Agreement reached, I sent back a reply that he was welcome to join Shazzog and I. We had thought to perhaps journey in to Nadox tonight, but we could stay in Dulak if he preferred. We would await him at the Portal Stone in Toxula.<br />
<br />
Then we sat down to wait for him. And we waited.<br />
Birds chirped. Crickets cricked.<br />
<br />
A minute or two later, he sent back a message. He had missed my reply, but was on his way.<br />
<br />
The cricket caught the notice of the bird. It was no longer cricking.<br />
<br />
***”Ummm, how long are you going to be? We are waiting for you in Toxula.”***<br />
<br />
A passing kobold decided to charge at us. As Shazzog and I looked up at it and started calling up magical blasts, it stopped.<br />
“Ummm, sorry, thought you were someone else. I’ll just be going now,” it grunted out as it fled.<br />
<br />
Thought so.<br />
<br />
***”Sorry! I’m getting a Virtue cast on me! IT WILL MAKE IT WAY EASY!”***<br />
(Yes, he sent that in all caps)<br />
<br />
The bird, too intent on eating the cricket, failed to notice the briar snake coming up behind it.<br />
Ah, the cycle of life is such a beautiful thing.<br />
<br />
“Where he at, Du? How long it take ta get da sparklies, anyway?”<br />
<br />
“Good question…perhaps he was <i>looking</i> for a Virtue?”<br />
<br />
***”You know, you don’t really need Virtue if you are having trouble finding it. I can use Temperance if needed, but I’ll barely need to heal you as it is.”***<br />
Kobold, meet briar snake. Briar snake, meet kobold. All we needed now was some background singers crooning out “Hakuna Matata”.<br />
<br />
Finally, a new message came from the warrior- ***“Had trouble finding a port. Found one and I’m on my way.”***<br />
<br />
Oh goody. Glad we’ve been waiting for him here in Toxula.<br />
***”So…Shazzog and I should just meet you in Gunthak, then?”****<br />
…<br />
***”Ummm, yeah.”*** was his reply.<br />
<br />
Sighing, for this was not boding well, we made our way through the Warrens and into StoneBrunt. From there, a quick trek brought us to the ship to Gunthak. A quick mental search showed that our little lost warrior had not arrived yet.<br />
<br />
***”Entering Gunthak now. Meet me at the Lighthouse near the Paladin”***<br />
There. Hopefully now we will actually get to see this wondrous slayer of beasties.<br />
<br />
A minute later, still no warrior. A quick look showed he is in the area, so maybe he was just arriving. I sent a repeat message. No response was forthcoming.<br />
<br />
A minute later, still no warrior.<br />
<br />
***”I see you are in the area, but I don’t see you. I’m at the lighthouse.”***<br />
<br />
Finally, a return message came through, ***”I’m at the beach. I’m invisible and running through the tunnels”***<br />
<br />
I can see we will need to work on our communication skills.<br />
***”Okay. Guess we are meeting you in Dulak, then?”***<br />
<br />
Shazzog drew his veil of magic across our images, hiding us from sight, and we began the last leg of our journey.<br />
<br />
When we arrived in Dulak, we finally found ourselves in the presence of the Great Halfling Warrior Bukkun. We know he is a Great Warrior because he reminds us every few seconds.<br />
<br />
Also joining us, apparently, is a female Halfling. In theory, she is a Cleric. So we were told, at any rate. <br />
(OOC: I also, at this point, made sure to tell them both in group that Shazzog and I were the same person. Couldn’t figure a way to fit that in the story.)<br />
<br />
“Hey, Du? Didn’t he say he just needed <i>a</i> cleric? Why he asking us if he got one already?”<br />
<br />
“Beats me. Perhaps the Great Halfling Warrior Bukkun plans on taking on such overwhelming forces that he feels he will need double the Holy Presence?”<br />
Shazzog looked at Bukkun rather skeptically.<br />
“Dat would be what…2 rats and maybe dat new guy dey got sweeping da docks?”<br />
<br />
(To Be Continued)</font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">

Rabbit Punching Death in the throat for 55 levels.<br><br />
Klan ov da Grok -Lanys
</font></p></p>
