	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 08-26-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">09:01 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">We underestimated the halfling’s abilities. No sooner did we organize ourselves than he was off to attack everything in sight.<br />
<br />
“We will just Crawl!” he said, “It’ll be better that way. You’ll see!”<br />
<br />
“Oh no!” cried the halfling cleric, “My clarity just died!”<br />
<br />
“This is Not Good. Note the capital letters,” I told Shazzog.<br />
<br />
The Great Halfling Warrior Bukkun decided he was Taking Charge of our group. He informed the half cleric that she was to ‘CHeal’ him at 30%, whereas I was to toss off ‘nukes’.<br />
<br />
Care to guess who was out of mana after 2 Complete Heals?<br />
The little Wanna Be A Cleric When She Grows Up sat down to regather her mystic energies.<br />
<br />
Shazzog and I, meanwhile are idly calling down Retribution and swarms of insects on everything the Great Halfling Warrior Bukkun runs across. Neither of us are taking too large a hit to our energies so far, but I am guessing that won’t last long if I am healing as well.<br />
<br />
“Shazzog, I know he won’t appreciate it, but why don’t you go ahead and buff the little guy? It’ll save me a lot of effort, and I will appreciate it.”<br />
<br />
We tried to tell the Great Halfling Warrior Bukkun to slow down and let Shazzog do his thing. TGHWB would have none of it. He was, in his words, ‘too focused on killing!’<br />
<br />
Shazzog and I shrugged between ourselves and Shazzog memorized all his protective magics and started casting them on TGHWB while he flailed at everything thing standing upright. I know better than to get in his way, so I just sat back and watched, keeping half an eye on TGHWB’s health as I did.<br />
<br />
Sure enough, he was in need of some Love of Innoruk by the time Shazzog was done. I had fully recharged by this point, so casting a complete Healing was easy enough.<br />
<br />
TGHWB apparently finally noticed something odd about Shazzog and my behaviour-<br />
***”Are you dual boxing? It’s okay if you are.”***<br />
<br />
Great, I’ve been given permission by The Great Halfling Warrior Bukken Himself to do what I have been doing for several months. I feel better now. I was worried about acceptance before.<br />
<br />
***”Yes. I said so at zone in.”***<br />
<br />
***”Oh. I didn’t pay attention. I am only focused on the killing!’***<br />
(No, I am not making that up)<br />
<br />
TGHWB went back to being a general menace to Dulak society.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, one of the new Dock Patrolmen, a Troll named Errol, wandered by.<br />
Errol is not the brightest Troll, but he does his job, and he takes it very seriously.<br />
<br />
His job is, among other things, to keep people from loitering. He noticed the Halfling sitting on the ground, and decided that qualified.<br />
<br />
“Errol? Why are you chasing my Halfling around in great big circles?” I asked him, when I noticed the commotion behind me.<br />
<br />
“Why is she running in great big circles?” he called back.<br />
<br />
This was a very good question, but one I did not have an answer to. Normally, when one is accosted while in the company of one’s compatriots, one will try to stand still long enough for aid to arrive. Someone apparently never told the Halfling cleric this. <br />
<br />
Round and round she went, with Errol in hot pursuit.<br />
We watched, for a minute, because it was a rather amusing sight. Finally we decided ‘enough is enough’.<br />
Shazzog and I took aim at Errol and prepared to end his shift a bit early.<br />
<br />
He noticed this and called over, “Ah, c’mon! Let me at least catch her first!”<br />
<br />
“Sorry, Errol. No can do. I like you, and all, but she is under my protection. No hard feelings. I’ll buy you a beer later.”<br />
<br />
Poor Errol. He has gotten to the point that he just cringes when we get to that part.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, TGHWB has finished beating up the warehouse workers, and finally notices that his pet cleric is in danger. He reaches Errol just about the time Errol slumps to the ground.<br />
<br />
“I’ve got over 5k hit points now! I’m UBER!”<br />
<br />
Shazzog shot me a dirty look and cast a blast of poison at TGHWB.<br />
“Whoops, miscast!” he grinned.<br />
“You and I both know that wasn’t going to actually get through anyway,” I said. “The Gods won’t let us attack each other.”<br />
<br />
“Yeah, well, I kin always hope dey not paying attention.”<br />
<br />
TGHWB went back to his harassment of the locals and I healed up the little cleric while she sat back down and bemoaned her lack of mana.<br />
<br />
Before long, we were back to the normal flow of the evening. TGHWB would go agro on everything in sight, I would throw out an occasional Retribution, Shazzog would summon clouds of insects, and every 10 seconds or so, TGHWB would advise everyone how he was ‘Uber’ and focused on the killing while the female Halfling bemoaned her lack of mana.<br />
<br />
Then something happened. There is a mysterious malady that afflicts adventurers, causing them to fall to the ground unconscious. For some reason, this is called ‘Link Death’. TGHWB may have been ‘Uber’ and ‘Really Powerful’, but he was not immune to this malady.</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
