</td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 08-26-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">09:02 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">Thud, down he went in mid battle.<br />
<br />
“Oh no! What are we going to do?” cried the little Halfling cleric.<br />
<br />
“Well, to begin with, I’m going to kill this guy that TGHWB keeled over on, then I am going to kill this guy that is trying desperately to beat on Shazzog. Feel free to jump in and melee if you want. I’ve got this covered.”<br />
<br />
“Me?”<br />
<br />
“Yep, you. Jump on in if you want. Or keep meditating. Up to you, but I find the ‘sit and heal’ bit kind of boring, myself.”<br />
<br />
“You mean I can actually do something!” she exclaimed, and jumped on in.<br />
A few moments later, we were done.<br />
<br />
“Never let anyone tell you that you can’t be a Battle Cleric,” I advised her.<br />
<br />
We sat and waited for TGHWB to regain consciousness. A few locals tried to object, but they were quickly persuaded to leave us be.<br />
<br />
Minutes went by…no TGHWB. Shazzog’s protections started to wear off us, so I decided we should go sit near the wall, out of traffic, while he recast them. I told the Halfling to follow me, and set off.<br />
<br />
Apparently, she is almost blind. She ran off in a completely different direction…right into a rather attractive dark elf scout.<br />
<br />
Round and round she goes…<br />
<br />
I was watching the grace and beauty of the dark elf female when Errol’s brother, Greg, came by.<br />
<br />
“G’morning, Duhikae. Shazzog. Fine day we are having.”<br />
<br />
“Hey, Greg. How’s it going? Sorry, I had to take out your brother a little while ago. You may want to go check on him.”<br />
<br />
“Errol? Yeah, I heard someone took him out again. Figures it was you. He’ll be fine, the medical here is pretty good.”<br />
<br />
“Glad to hear it. Hey, who is that dark elf chasing my Halfling over there? I haven’t seen her before.”<br />
<br />
“Her? That’s Judi. Yeah, she’s new. Single, too,” Greg grinned at me. “Want I should introduce you?”<br />
<br />
“Could you? That’d be great! Still, I’m going to have to blast her…probably not the best first impression a guy could make…”<br />
<br />
“Naw, I’ll cover for ya. I’ll go run in and ‘join’ her. Then you can always say she got caught in the blast radius. Make ya look even more powerful.”<br />
<br />
“Thanks, Greg. You are the best! Shazzog, lets do this!”<br />
<br />
Greg made a big show of running at the Halfling while waving his cutlass and screaming, and Shazzog and I let loose with pretty much every show off spell we had. <br />
<br />
I went and collected the rather shaken cleric and brought her back to the wall.<br />
<br />
We were just about done getting all our protections recast when TGHWB finally showed up again. He was surprised to see us still alive and healthy, I think, because he asked if Shazzog and I were somehow not ‘KOS’.<br />
<br />
Shazzog and I laughed at that, and continued casting our protections.<br />
<br />
Apparently, the Halflings were conversing amongst themselves, because they asked Shazzog to make them invisible.<br />
<br />
“Think the little cleric has to go change her armor?” <br />
<br />
Shazzog snickered, “Yep. Wanna take bets dey ain’t coming back?”<br />
<br />
He cast his veil of invisibility on them, and off they ran. Sure enough, they were out of Dulak in no time at all.<br />
<br />
“Dey still grouped wid us. Why youse tink dey still grouped wid us?”<br />
<br />
“Dunno. Let’s let it stay like that a few and see what they say when they forget we can still hear them. Want to go set up in the corner like normal?”<br />
<br />
“Sure ting, let’s go. Hey, youse gotta member ta send dat Judi some flowers er sumptin ta ‘agologize’ fer taking her down on her fist day like dat.”<br />
<br />
“Good plan. We’ll stop on the way.”<br />
<br />
Off we went. The Shady Salesman across from the Hungry Shark has an FTD franchise, so I was able to place an order with him. He promised to have them delivered within the hour.<br />
<br />
Our corner was empty, as it usually is. A while back, one of the local guards hung a ‘Reserved’ sign in it as a joke. Apparently, people believed it, because we seldom found anyone there.<br />
<br />
We were chatting with the fisherman that hangs out there when we noticed TGHWB saying, “Invite L___”<br />
<br />
“Uh oh, Duhikae. I tink dey coming back!”<br />
<br />
“Worse, it sounds like they are bringing more. Do we really want to take that chance?”<br />
<br />
Neither of us did.<br />
<br />
Using the linked bond we had as a group, I said, “Hey, I’m being called to a Kael Raid to help take out Vindi. You guys going to be okay?”<br />
This was not a complete fabrication. Our guild, along with the Alliance, was indeed in Kael at that very moment. I hoped we would be able to get there in time to do some good, but knew that staring at the entrance to Kael and counting bricks was preferable to staying in Dulak if TGHWB was coming back. I hoped by using that as an excuse, I could find a way to leave politely, without having to hurt any ones feelings.<br />
<br />
<br />
Almost instantly, TGHWB sent back, ***”Dude, can I come? I have a 65 Cleric that needs faction!”***<br />
<br />
/cry<br />
<br />
My query as to status of the Kael Invasion was answered about that time, “Vindi just went down a few minutes ago. Wrapping it up here.”<br />
***”I’m being told Vindi is down now. Not sure what they need me for.”***<br />
(Hey, technically that was true.)<br />
<br />
Shazzog and I watched as the two Halflings disappeared from our group.<br />
<br />
“You tink dey be okay widout us? Dat little warrior was kinda annoying but dat cleric seemed okay enuf. She just young and don’t know what she can do.”<br />
<br />
“True enough, Shazz. Perhaps we should help her out.”<br />
<br />
The Iksar in charge of the local watch was patrolling nearby, so we called him over.<br />
“Sslith! Just the man we were looking for! Hey, listen. There are a couple of Halflings that will probably be coming back soon. One of ‘em thinks he is a Great Warrior. Calls himself Bukkun. Take care of ‘em for me, will you? We have to go to Kael to help with an invasion.”<br />
<br />
“Kael, eh? Ssssure you do. Let’sss just be clear here, ssshall we? The important part isss that they will no longer be under your protection, yesss?”<br />
<br />
“Yep, you got it. That’s why I’m coming to you. I know you will take good care of them.”<br />
<br />
“Yessss, that I will. I’ll sssend some of my boysss over now to greet them. By the way, I jussst came from the infirmary. Errol and Greg sssay you owe them both beersss and Judi sssays ‘Thank You’ for the flowersssss.”<br />
<br />
Sweet!<br />
<br />
Shazzog and I opened our gate and stepped back through to the Plane of Knowledge. Further chatting with my Alliance indicated that while Vindi may be down, someone wanted help taking out Wurms in the Great Divide. Sounded perfect to us.<br />
<br />
“Duhikae? Dat cleric we was with…she seemed to scared ta be out in places like Dulak. Why you tink dat is? How come she not like you?”<br />
<br />
“Not everyone has a powerful Troll Shaman to keep them company, Big Guy. If I hadn’t met you that day in Neriak, who knows where I would be now? I’d probably be even worse off than her. At least she wasn’t chained up.”<br />
<br />
“Dat’s true. Anybody try ta chain youse up now, though, they gotta go through me first. Not ta mention da rest of da Klan. Let’s go kill us some wurms.”<br />
<br />
And so we did.<br />
<br />
<br />
The End</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
	<p></p>
